Squeeze the @Steamed Brown Basmati Rice{1%pouch} to separate the grains. Tear a strip approx 2cm along the top. Cook the rice according to pack instructions.

Meanwhile, peel the @Kiwi{1}, then cut into 1cm chunks. Halve the @Red Chilli{1} lengthways, deseed, then finely chop. Zest and halve the @Lime{1}.

Pop the kiwi and chilli (add less if you'd prefer things milder) into a #medium bowl{}. Squeeze in half the lime juice, then add the @Sugar{1/2%tsp} and @Olive Oil{1%tbsp} for the salsa. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, mix together, then set aside.

Peel and grate the @Garlic Cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain the @Sweetcorn{160%grams} in a #sieve{}. Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, add the sweetcorn and cook until charred, ~{5-6%minutes}. Adjust the heat if necessary. Stir only twice during this time - you want the sweetcorn to pick up some nice colour. Transfer the charred corn to a #bowl{}. Set aside.

Meanwhile, drain the @King Prawns{150%grams}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Wipe out the (now empty) #frying pan{}, then put back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil. Once hot, add the prawns, garlic and @Caribbean Style Jerk{1%sachet}. Stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the charred corn, @Tomato Puree{30%grams}, @Vegetable Stock Paste{10%grams} and @Water{100%ml} for the sauce to the prawns. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat slightly and simmer for ~{3-4%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Remove the pan from the heat. Stir in the @Mango Chutney{40%grams} and @Butter{20%grams} until melted. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash of water if the sauce is a little too thick.

Share the rice between #bowls{}. Spoon over the Caribbean style prawns, spooning over any remaining sauce from the pan. Serve the kiwi salsa alongside. Sprinkle with the lime zest to finish.

Enjoy!